{[%evp 0,23,44,16,37,-29,54,46,84,55,64,7,68,64,76,83,66,66,96,34,49,39,78,28,
109,84]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. h4 {Everyone, who is a 1.
d4 player encountered a problem - what to do against the Gruenfeld Defence? It
is a sound opening where Black attacks White's center from the very beginning.
In many lines, the theory goes so far that many games end in a forced draw
without even a single own move from both players. This is always disappointing
for the White players. In the current survey, I will present a very aggressive
line 5.h4. First of all, let me clarify one thing. You will not find here a
refutation of the Gruenfeld, but if you are an ambitious player, this might be
an interesting line to include in your repertoire. So, what is the point
behind such an early push of a side pawn? White is ready to push this pawn
further h4-h5 and even sacrifice it. This should drive Black's knight away
from the center and Black will lose control over the key squares d5 and e4.
Also, the h-file will be opened for White's rook. This will become obvious
after Black castles to the kingside and his monarch might get under dangerous
attack.} h6 $6 (5... h5 $6 6. Bg5 c6 ({After} 6... Ne4 7. cxd5 Nxc3 8. bxc3
Qxd5 9. e3 {White gets a pleasant position. He will develop the bishop to d3
and then will push his center forward.}) 7. e3 O-O 8. Qb3 $14 {1-0 (43)
Santiago,Y (2507)-Goncalves,J (1982) Ponta Grossa 2017}) (5... Bg4 6. Ne5 $1 (
6. Qb3 $6 c5 $1 {Typical pawn sacrifice in the Gruenfeld.} 7. Qxb7 Nbd7 {
Black got good compensation for the pawn. White is somewhat lagging in
development - Esipenko,A (2571)-Dubov,D (2694) Moscow 2018 (0-1, 26).}) 6...
Be6 (6... dxc4 7. Nxg4 Nxg4 8. e4 $14 ({The solid} 8. e3 $14 {is also good.}))
(6... c5 $6 7. cxd5 $16) 7. h5 $1 {distracting the knight away from the center.
} Nxh5 (7... gxh5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Rxh5 $14) 8. Qb3 {[%csl Rb7,Rd5] Black is in
trouble.}) (5... e6 {is possible, but somewhat passive and not exactly in the
spirit of the Gruenfeld. White is slightly better after} 6. Bf4 {followed by 7.
e3 and further development.}) (5... Nc6 $6 {doesn't make sense. After} 6. h5 {
Black will have to either allow h5-h6 or make a concession.}) 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7.
e4 Nxc3 8. bxc3 {This is almost identical to one of the main lines of the
Gruenfeld, but the inclusion of moves h2-h4 and h7-h6 clearly favours White.}
c5 9. Rb1 {This move seems to be White's most precise reaction since in the
systems based on Rb1 the inclusion of the moves h2-h4 and h7-h6 is clearly in
White's favour.} ({Another interesting option is} 9. Be3 Qa5 10. Qd2 Nd7 ({
Maybe Black should play} 10... Nc6 11. Rc1 cxd4 12. cxd4 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 O-O 14.
d5 Rd8 {1/2 (40) Zufic,M (2462)-Jukic,B (2375) Mali Losinj 2016. Once again,
we have a theoretical position with moves h2-h4 and h7-h6 included. Obviously,
such an inclusion favours White since in many lines the h6-pawn will be
hanging. Nevertheless, it is not easy to find something concrete.}) 11. Bd3 e5
12. d5 {White got a stable advantage in the game Fridman,D (2635)-Kantans,T 
(2487) Neustadt an der Weinstrasse 2018 (1-0, 38).}) 9... O-O (9... Qa5 $6 10.
Rb5 $16) 10. Be2 cxd4 {This is the most principled reaction.} ({Too risky is} 
10... b6 {since the inclusion of the move h2-h4 and ...h7-h6 allows White to
follow with} 11. h5 $1 $146 {thus weakening Black's kingside structure.
Strangely enough, this natural move turns out to be a novelty.} (11. Be3 Bb7
12. d5 {This is the solid approach to the position.} ({Here, once again, White
could have played} 12. h5 g5 {This move transposes to the lines which were
examined above.} ({This move order gives Black the option of playing} 12...
Bxe4 {Here, I managed to find the following sequence:} 13. hxg6 Bxg6 14. Qc1 h5
15. Nh4 Bxb1 16. Qxb1 cxd4 17. Bg5 Nd7 18. Nf5 Nf6 19. Rh3 dxc3 20. Qc1 $40 {
With a very dangerous initiative. In a practical game White's attack would be
practically winning.}) 13. e5) 12... e6 13. c4 {White keeps a slight edge. 0-1
(46) Mareco,S (2649)-Ivanchuk,V (2710) Batumi 2018}) 11... g5 12. Be3 {By
protecting the d4-pawn, White starts preparing Nxg5.} ({Another interesting
possibility is} 12. Bxg5 hxg5 13. h6 Bf6 14. e5 Bf5 15. exf6 exf6 (15... Bxb1
$2 16. Qxb1 exf6 17. O-O $16) 16. O-O Nc6 17. Rb5 $13 {The position is
balanced. Nevertheless, Black is still under a slight pressure.}) 12... Bb7 13.
e5 $1 {One more preparatory move.} ({The immediate} 13. Nxg5 {is well met by}
e5 $1 {when the arising positions are very unclear.}) 13... cxd4 14. cxd4 Nc6
15. Nxg5 $1 {This sacrifice works now.} hxg5 (15... Nxe5 16. dxe5 hxg5 17. f4
Qxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Bxg2 19. Rg1 Bc6 20. Rxg5 $14) 16. h6 Bxe5 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18.
Bxg5 $36 {White keeps the initiative thanks to his bishop pair and safer king.}
) ({With moves h2-h4 and h7-h6 included, this move (popular in the theoretical
position) would be a mistake. White can just play} 10... Nc6 $2 11. d5 Ne5 $140
12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Bxh6 {winning a pawn. With pawns on h2 and h7, White's main
move is Qd2.}) (10... Qa5 11. Rb5 Qxc3+ 12. Bd2 Qa3 13. Rxc5 Nc6 (13... Qxa2
14. Qc1 {[%cal Gc5c8,Gd2h6]} Nc6 15. Bc4 Qa4 16. O-O $16) 14. Rc3 Qxa2 15. d5
$1 Na5 (15... Ne5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Rc2 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gd2h6]}) 16. Rc2 Qa3
17. O-O {[%cal Gd1b1,Gd2b4]}) 11. cxd4 Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Qxa2 13. O-O {When the
pawns are on h2 and h7 respectively, this is a well known theoretical position.
The inclusion of the moves h2-h4 and h7-h6 favours White.} Bg4 ({One game saw} 
13... Qe6 14. Qc2 Qc6 {1/2 (47) Tosic,M (2415)-Zontakh,A (2580) Mataruska
Banja 1996. In this position, the simpest would have been} 15. Qd3 {[%cal
Gf1c1,Gd3e3,Gd2c3,Gd4d5] Leaving Black underdeveloped. Also, Black will have
to waste time on improving the position of the queen. On the other hand,
White's play is pretty straightforward. He can follow with simple moves like
Rfc1, Bc3 and d4-d5 thus exchanging the dark-squared bishops.}) (13... Nc6 14.
d5 Na5 15. Bb4 Bd7 {1-0 (44) Halkias,S (2584)-Gauglitz,G (2397) Germany 2009
Here, the move} 16. e5 $16 {[%cal Gb1a1] would have given White a huge
advantage.}) 14. Rxb7 Nd7 (14... Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Bxd4 16. e5 Na6 {If the pawns
would be on h2 and h7, this position is playable for Black, but here the pawn
is simply hanging:} 17. Bxh6 $18) 15. h5 $1 {White was in possession of an
initiative in the game Peralta,F (2557)-Alsina Leal,D (2523) Barcelona 2009 
(½-½, 41).} *

