{[%evp 0,23,17,16,28,5,54,46,72,39,58,6,79,93,84,66,79,71,71,59,68,68,75,75,75,
56]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. h4 c5 $6 {A standart
counterstrike, but it's too early for this.} 6. dxc5 Qa5 (6... Na6 7. cxd5 Qa5
({too risky is} 7... Nxc5 8. Be3 {[%cal Ge3d4] This is the most solid
continuation. The bishop is going to occupy the d4-square, thus neutralizing
it's counterpart on g7.} b6 9. Bd4 O-O 10. b4 $16 {White got a huge advantage
in 1-0 (35) Wagner,D (2558)-Salem,A (2642) Biel 2018}) 8. Bd2 $1 (8. Nd2 $6 {
Not the best way to target the black queen as this move obstructs the
development of White's queenside.} Nxc5 9. Nc4 Qb4 {was completely unclear in
the game Nepomniachtchi,I (2717)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2719) Biel 2013 (0-1, 63).}
) 8... Nxc5 9. e4 {Here White can develop his pieces smoothly and enjoy his
healthy extra pawn.}) 7. cxd5 Nxd5 (7... Ne4 8. Bd2 Nxc3 (8... Nxd2 9. Qxd2
Qxc5 10. Rc1 O-O 11. e4 {White has a winning advantage. 1-0 (27) Rasmussen,A 
(2486)-Agopov,M (2435) Warsaw 2013}) 9. Bxc3 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Qxc3+ 11. Nd2 Na6
12. Rc1 Qa5 13. Qc2 $16 {White's advantage is out of question.}) (7... O-O 8.
Nd2 {[%cal Gd2b3,Gc1e3,Ge3d4,Gg2g3,Gf1g2] This move introduces an interesting
concept. White is planning to neutralize Black's dark-squared bishop by means
of Nd2-b3 followed by Bc1-e3-d4. Later on, he can develop the light-squared
bishop via g2.} Qxc5 9. Nb3 Qb6 {This move only helps White.} ({More tenacious
would have been} 9... Qb4 {In this case, White can transform his material
advantage in a positional one.} 10. g3 Ne4 11. Bg2 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Bxc3+ 13. Bd2
Bxd2+ 14. Nxd2 $16 {[%cal Ge1g1,Ga1b1] White has more space and active pieces.}
) 10. Be3 Qd8 11. g3 b6 12. Bg2 Bb7 13. O-O Na6 14. Bd4 $18 {1-0 (50)
Protopopova,A (2308)-Lysenko,M (2210) Kolomna 2018}) (7... Qxc5 $6 {allows
White to execute to transfer his bishop to d4 with a tempo.} 8. Be3 $16 {
[%cal Ge3d4]}) 8. Qxd5 Bxc3+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ ({After} 9... Be6 10. Qxb7 Bxd2+ 11.
Nxd2 O-O 12. b4 Qa4 13. e3 {Black does not have sufficient compensation for
the pawns. For example:} Rd8 (13... Nd7 14. a3 a5 15. Bb5 Qc2 16. Bxd7 Rfb8 17.
Qe4 Qxe4 18. Nxe4 Bxd7 19. Kd2 axb4 20. axb4 Rxa1 21. Rxa1 Rxb4 22. f3 $16) 14.
a3 Qc2 15. Rd1 Nd7 16. Ba6 $16 {[%cal Ge1g1]}) 10. Qxd2 Qxd2+ (10... Qxc5 11.
Rc1 Qf5 12. Nd4 Qd7 13. h5 $16 {1-0 (21) Dreev,A (2673)-Wantiez,F (2301)
Warsaw 2013}) 11. Kxd2 $1 ({White won several games after} 11. Nxd2 {but, I
find the recapture by the king even stronger.}) 11... O-O (11... Bf5 12. e3 O-O
13. Bc4 Rd8+ 14. Ke2 Nd7 15. b4 a5 16. a3 $16) 12. e4 {Followed by Bf1-d3, one
of the rooks to c1, the king possibly to e3. White is simply a pawn up for no
compensation.} *

