{[%evp 0,61,28,28,16,-20,50,36,84,56,67,6,20,23,39,22,26,26,42,26,201,88,220,
126,222,10,231,169,210,222,322,329,410,271,253,232,205,235,254,276,276,264,340,
329,359,376,375,314,310,335,380,408,408,421,433,506,527,535,541,554,547,579,
761,793]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. h4 dxc4 6. e4 O-O ({After
} 6... Bg4 7. Bxc4 O-O 8. e5 Nh5 ({After} 8... Nfd7 9. h5 $1 {Black is in
trouble. White's kingside attack is getting very dangerous.} gxh5 {1-0 (31)
Morozevich,A (2748)-Giri,A (2720) Beijing 2012} ({The move} 9... Nb6 {doesn't
help either.} 10. Bb3 c5 ({Another game saw} 10... Nc6 11. hxg6 hxg6 12. Qd3
$18 {[%cal Gd3g6] With a decisive attack. 1-0 (25) Gallego Alcaraz,A (2387)
-Mendoza,R (2360) Quibdo 2015}) 11. hxg6 hxg6 12. Rh4 $1 cxd4 13. Rxg4 dxc3 {
1-0 (30) Fridman,D (2627)-Hansen,E (2584) Rabat 2014. At this point, the
simplest would have been} 14. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 15. Qc2 $18 {[%cal Gc2g6] winning
on the spot.}) 10. Qc2 $1 {[%cal Gf3g5] This is more precise than the game
continuation 10.Qd3.} e6 ({The natural} 10... h6 $2 {runs into} 11. Bxh6 $1
Bxh6 $140 12. Qg6+ Bg7 13. Ng5 {With mate in 4.}) 11. Ng5 Bf5 12. Bd3 $1 {
The point behind 10.Qc2.} Bg6 13. Bxg6 hxg6 14. Rxh5 $18) 9. Be2 Nc6 10. Be3 {
white's center is stable. Black's knight on h5 is misplaced.}) 7. Bxc4 c5 (7...
Bg4 8. e5 {is just a transposition.}) 8. d5 b5 $1 {Typical counterstrike in
this kind of structure.} 9. Bxb5 Nxe4 10. Nxe4 Qa5+ {Exploiting the fact that
white's king is still in the center.} 11. Nc3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qxb5 {Black
managed to open up the position and exchange a pair of light pieces. He didn't
sacrifice any material for that. However, he had to give his dark-squared
bishop - an extremely useful and valuable piece in Gruenfeld Defence.} 13. h5
Qc4 $1 ({The development of the bishop instead wouldn't make Black's life
easier:} 13... Bg4 14. Bh6 Rd8 15. hxg6 hxg6 16. Rh4 Qd7 17. c4 {and the
weakness of the black king will tell sooner or later.}) (13... Bf5 14. hxg6
fxg6 (14... hxg6 $2 15. Ne5 f6 16. Ng4 $40) 15. Rh4 $1 $36 {The rook is very
effective on the 4th rank.}) (13... Bd7 $2 14. hxg6 fxg6 15. Qd2 $1 $18 {
[%cal Gd2h6]}) (13... Nd7 $6 14. Rh4 $16) 14. hxg6 fxg6 15. Rh4 $1 {White can
sacrifice the pawn.} Qxc3+ 16. Bd2 Qd3 17. Bh6 $1 (17. Bg5 Qxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Rf5
19. Re4 Bb7 20. Rxe7 Bxd5 21. Re8+ Kf7 22. Re7+ Kg8 23. Re8+ Kf7 24. Re7+ Kg8 {
1/2-1/2 (24) Edouard,R (2634)-Istratescu,A (2619) Saint-Quentin 2015}) 17...
Qxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Re8 {The queens are off, Black has an extra pawn, but White
still has resources to cause troubles to the second player.} 19. Ng5 $1 {
[%cal Gh4f4,Gf4f7]} Nd7 20. Ne6 Rb8 21. Nc7 Rd8 22. Ne6 Re8 23. Nc7 Rd8 24. Re4
Rb7 (24... Kf7 25. Ne6 Re8 26. d6 Nf6 27. Ng5+ Kg8 28. Rxe7 Bd7 $14) 25. d6 $1
(25. Bf4 $6 Rb4 26. Rxb4 cxb4 $11) 25... exd6 (25... e5 $5 26. f4 Rb4 27. Rxb4
cxb4 28. Bg5 Rf8 29. Ne6 Re8 30. Be7 Bb7 31. Nc7 Rc8 32. fxe5 Nxe5 33. d7 Nxd7
34. Rxd7 Bc6 35. Rd8+ Rxd8 36. Bxd8 Bxg2 37. Na6 Kf7 38. Nxb4 Ke6 {Black
should hold this endgame.}) 26. Ne8 $1 {I suspect that all this was a part of
home preparation, but it doesn't make White's moves less impressive.} Rb4 27.
Re3 Bb7 $2 (27... Ba6 28. f3 $36 (28. Rxd6 $6 Rb1+ 29. Kd2 Rb6 30. Nf6+ Kf7 31.
Rxd7+ Rxd7+ 32. Nxd7 Rd6+ $11)) 28. Rxd6 Rd4 (28... Rb1+ 29. Kd2 Rb6 30. Nf6+
Kf7 31. Rxd7+ Rxd7+ 32. Nxd7 Rd6+ 33. Rd3 $18 {That's the point. This move
wouldn't be possible if Black's bishop would be on a6.}) 29. Bg5 Rxd6 30. Nxd6
Rb8 31. Re7 Bc6 32. Bh6 Kh8 33. Nf7+ Kg8 34. Ng5 Ne5 {There is no defense.
Black has to give a piece.} 35. Rxe5 Rb1+ 36. Kd2 {1-0 (36) Riazantsev,A (2651)
-Kokarev,D (2636) Novosibirsk 2016} *

