{[%evp 0,50,19,25,23,8,54,37,67,50,61,24,12,-34,-23,-27,-5,-56,-58,-43,-45,-51,
-33,-71,-52,-52,-57,-72,-57,-45,-6,-6,-3,-3,-32,-39,4,-19,71,-18,90,65,56,69,
60,31,31,31,38,38,29,28,24]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. h4 c6
6. Bg5 {This is White's most ambitious approach. With his last move, he is
putting an indirect pressure on Black's center since the f6-knight supports
the central pawn. At the same time, in many cases, White can execute the
advance h4-h5 after taking on f6. Black has possible options in this position
- 6...Ne4, 6...dxc4, 6...0-0, and 6...h6. The last two moves are dealt with in
the next chapter.} dxc4 (6... Ne4 7. e3 Nxg5 (7... Qa5 8. Rc1 $1 $146 {
According to my database, this is a novelty and a strong improvement over the
most popular 8.Qb3. White starts fighting for the initiative and gives the
a2-pawn away.} Nxc3 9. Rxc3 Qxa2 10. Qc1 {[%cal Gc3a3] Creating the threat of
Ra3 on the next move.} Qa5 11. cxd5 Qxd5 12. Bc4 Qa5 13. e4 {with an excellent
compensation for the pawn. White controls the center and is ahead in
development.}) ({After} 7... h6 {White's play is simple:} 8. Bf4 O-O 9. Bd3
Nxc3 10. bxc3 dxc4 11. Bxc4 $14 {1-0 (74) Mamedyarov,S (2757)-Le,Q (2703)
Beijing 2013}) (7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 O-O 9. h5 {This is the most ambitious
approach.} ({The solid} 9. Be2 $14 {gave White an edge in 1-0 (32) Gareyev,T 
(2640)-Dale,A (2305) Arlington 2014}) 9... Nd7 ({After} 9... h6 {White has a
promising piece sacrifice:} 10. Bxh6 $1 Bxh6 11. hxg6 $40) 10. hxg6 hxg6 11.
Bd3 Nf6 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Qc2 $16 {1-0 (20) Brown,M (2524)-Wang,K (2450)
Charlotte 2019}) 8. hxg5 {This structure is good for White. The h-file is open
in his favour and the pawn on g5 yields some extra space. Black has a pair of
bishops, but they don't have enough room to become a significant factor.} e6 {
With this move, Black makes sure that in the case of cxd5, he can always
recapture with the e-pawn. At the same time, the f3-knight is now tied to the
defense of the g5-pawn.} ({The attempt to get rid of the g5-pawn by playing} 
8... h5 {deserves attention.} 9. gxh6 Rxh6 10. Rxh6 Bxh6 11. Bd3 $14 {White
keeps an edge in this position. Later on, he can play Qc2 followed by 0-0-0.
Black's kingside is somewhat vulnerable. In some cases, bishop sacrifices on
g6 can work. 1-0 (33) Mozharov,M (2573)-Lagno,K (2523) Moscow 2015}) 9. e4 dxe4
10. Nxe4 Qa5+ 11. Qd2 Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2 $14 {This endgame is favorable for White.
He has more space and more active pieces. Black's bishop pair is not a factor
in this position. 1-0 (31) Mamedyarov,S (2757)-Karjakin,S (2756) Beijing 2013})
7. e4 {It is curious that Ian Nepomniachtchi handled played this position from
both sides.} Be6 {This is the solid approach to the position.} ({The most
popular option is} 7... b5 {when the main line goes} 8. e5 Nd5 9. h5 h6 $2 {
Several strong grandmasters played this bad move, which shows the complexity
and practical problems that Black might face in this line. It's so easy to go
astray!} ({The move} 9... Na6 {was played only once. Here, I suggest a novelty:
} 10. a4 {immediately challenging the stability of the queenside.} Nac7 11.
Nxd5 Qxd5 ({The idea behind 10.a4 can be seen after} 11... Nxd5 12. h6 $1 {
important intermezzo which deprives Black from castling.} Bf8 13. axb5 cxb5 14.
b3 $1 {It turns out that Black cannot hold the queenside structure together.})
12. h6 Bf8 13. Be2 Bf5 14. O-O Qd7 15. Qc1 {White doesn't have immediate
threats but has long-term compensation. The break b2-b3 is in the air. It's
difficult for Black to complete the development, which means that his king
will be stuck in the center for a while.}) ({The same long-term compensation
White has after} 9... Bg4 10. h6 Bf8 11. a4 $44) ({or} 9... Bf5 10. h6 Bf8 11.
a4 $44) (9... gxh5 {is possible, but ruins Black's structure.} 10. Rxh5 Bg4 11.
Rh4 h5 12. Be2 {The position is unclear, but again from practical point of
view easier to handle for White.}) 10. hxg6 $1 (10. Bd2 $2 g5 $15 {0-1 (39)
Iotov,V (2579)-Durarbayli,V (2632) New York 2015}) 10... hxg5 ({Black can
decline the piece offer, but then his kingside is permanently weakened. An
extra pawn is a low price for that.} 10... fxg6 11. Bd2 Nxc3 (11... Nd7 12. a4
Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nf8 14. Nh4 $1 $16 {1-0 (35) Espinosa Veloz,E (2504)-Gledura,B 
(2486) Santa Clara 2015}) (11... Be6 12. a4 Nxc3 13. bxc3 $44) 12. bxc3 Be6 13.
a4 $16 {0-1 (52) Stopa,J (2479)-Bernadskiy,V (2540) Mumbai 2016}) 11. Rxh8+
Bxh8 12. gxf7+ Kxf7 13. Nxg5+ Kg6 14. Qf3 $1 Nxc3 (14... Kxg5 15. Qg3+ Kh6 16.
O-O-O Qe8 17. Nxd5 $1 cxd5 18. Be2 Qg6 19. Qh4+ Kg7 20. Qxe7+ Qf7 21. Qh4 $1
$18 {[%cal Gd1h1]}) 15. bxc3 Kxg5 {So far we are following the game
Nepomniachtchi,I (2721)-Giri,A (2734) Beijing 2013 (1-0, 26). Here White had a
forced win, not trivial at all, though:} 16. Qg3+ Kh6 (16... Kf5 17. Be2 Ke6
18. Bg4+ Kf7 19. Bh5+ Kf8 20. Qf4+ Bf6 21. exf6 exf6 22. Kd2 $18 {[%cal Ga1e1]}
) 17. Bd3 $3 {Preventing Black's king from escaping to h7 and also the
manoeuvre Qd8-e8-g6.} cxd3 18. Kd2 Qe8 19. Rh1+ Qh5 20. Rxh5+ Kxh5 21. Qh2+ Kg6
22. Qxh8 $18) 8. e5 Nd5 9. h5 Nd7 10. h6 $1 {White can't make an immediate
benefit from the "h" file, but can kick away the black bishop.} Bf8 {Now it
will be difficult for Black to castle.} 11. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4d6]} f6 {It's a
certain concession, but without this move Black won't be able to complete the
development.} ({An alternative is} 11... Qb6 {when White should play} 12. Bxc4
$1 $146 ({After} 12. Rc1 f6 {Black was fine in 1/2 (33) Chekletsov,I (2379)
-Kulaots,K (2554) Riga 2018}) 12... Qb4+ (12... Qxb2 {is very risky. White
gets an obvious advantage after the following forced sequence} 13. Rb1 Nc3 14.
Rxb2 Nxd1 15. Rc2 Bxc4 16. Rxc4 Nb2 17. Rc2 Na4 18. e6 fxe6 19. Bf4 {[%cal
Ge4g5]}) 13. Nfd2 b5 14. Bxd5 cxd5 (14... Bxd5 15. Rh4 $1 Qxb2 16. a4 $44 {
White has a big advantage. It is not clear how Black can complete the
development.}) 15. Nc3 Qxd4 16. Nxb5 Qxe5+ 17. Be3 $44 {Once again, Black
faces serious development problems.}) 12. Bd2 b5 (12... Bf5 13. Ng3 Bd3 14.
Bxd3 cxd3 15. Qb3 Qb6 16. Qxd3 $14 {Now the greedy} Qxb2 $6 {is not
recommended. This pawn is those poisoned. For instance:} 17. O-O Qb5 18. Qc2 {
[%cal Ga1b1] and later White will use the b-file for an attack. The black king
will never be safe.}) 13. a4 Bf5 14. Ng3 e6 15. Nxf5 exf5 16. axb5 cxb5 17. Be2
$6 (17. exf6 $1 Qxf6 18. b3 $1 {would be the best way to ruin Black's pawns
chain on the queenside.}) 17... Be7 $6 ({An immediate} 17... a5 {was
preferable.}) 18. O-O a5 19. b3 c3 20. Bxb5 cxd2 21. e6 O-O 22. exd7 $6 ({After
} 22. Bxd7 $1 {White would keep a steady plus.}) 22... Nc3 23. Bc4+ Kh8 24.
Qxd2 Ne4 25. Qe3 Qxd7 $11 {0-1 (37) Kasparov,G (2812)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2751)
Saint Louis 2017} *

