1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. h4 c6 6. Bg5 h6 (6... O-O 7. Bxf6
Bxf6 8. e3 (8. h5 {Many strong grandmasters pushed this pawn automatically,
but I don't think it's necessary.} g5 {Black has good statistics in this
position.} (8... Bf5 9. e3 e6 10. hxg6 Bxg6 11. Bd3 Nd7 12. Qe2 e5 13. Bxg6
hxg6 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. cxd5 cxd5 16. Rd1 $14 {1/2-1/2 (23) Grischuk,A (2764)
-Carlsen,M (2872) London 2013}) 9. e3 (9. e4 dxe4 10. Nxe4 h6 11. Nxf6+ exf6 {
This structure is good for Black as his king is now very safe. The pawn on h5
can become a target in any endgame.} 12. Qd2 Re8+ 13. Be2 Bg4 14. O-O-O Nd7 15.
Rhe1 Qc7 $15 {0-1 (57) Nisipeanu,L (2674)-Caruana,F (2779) Bucharest 2013})
9... h6 10. Qb3 e6 11. O-O-O Nd7 12. e4 Bg7 13. cxd5 exd5 14. exd5 c5 $1 $44 {
0-1 (25) Forcen Esteban,D (2565)-Ponomariov,R (2706) Madrid 2016}) 8... h6 (
8... h5 {is possible, of course. Now I recommend to develop the bishop to e2.
After} 9. Be2 {White has an idea Nf3-g5, followed by a g2-g4 thrust. He also
keeps an option of castling to the queenside. I wouldn't claim that White is
better, but he has practically dangerous ideas at his disposal.}) 9. Qc2 e6 10.
O-O-O Nd7 {would transpose to the main line 6...h6, analyzed in this chapter.})
7. Bxf6 Bxf6 8. e3 {Another option is 8.h5, but there is no need to hurry up
with this advance. The developing move 8.e3 is more flexible.} e6 {Very solid
move, strengthening the center.} 9. Qc2 Nd7 10. O-O-O {This is the most
ambitious plan.} O-O {Opposite side castlings usually hint on a sharp battle.}
11. Kb1 Bg7 12. g4 ({At this point, I suggest the following plan for White:} 
12. e4 $1 b6 (12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 Qe7 14. g4 {White keeps an option of
developing his bishop also to g2, for example:} b6 15. Bg2 Bb7 16. g5 h5 17. c5
{gaining more space. White is better in this structure.}) 13. e5 Bb7 14. cxd5
$1 $146 {In my opinion, White should immediately clarify the situation in the
center.} (14. Rh3 $13 {1-0 (54) Mamedyarov,S (2817)-Praggnanandhaa,R (2530)
Kolkata 2018}) 14... exd5 ({Worse is} 14... cxd5 {due to} 15. Nb5 $16 {[%cal
Gb5d6,Gh4h5] After occupying the d6-square, White can further weaken Black's
kingside by means of h4-h5.}) 15. Bd3 c5 16. h5 cxd4 (16... c4 17. Be2 $16) 17.
Nb5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. hxg6 $40) 12... Qe7 13. cxd5 (13. h5 g5 14. cxd5
exd5 15. Bd3 Nb6 {is okay for Black.}) 13... exd5 14. Bd3 Nb6 15. Rhg1 Bd7 16.
Ne5 Bxe5 17. dxe5 Qxe5 18. f4 Qxe3 19. Bxg6 Qxf4 20. g5 fxg6 21. Qxg6+ Kh8 22.
Qxh6+ Kg8 23. Qg6+ Kh8 24. Qh6+ Kg8 25. Qg6+ {1/2-1/2 (25) Tomashevsky,E (2696)
-Svidler,P (2755) Moscow 2017} *

